<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-234-458  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 234 458.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Communications  Jan-Feb 1990 v13 n1 p37(11).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fibre optic LAN systems and costs. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Herskowitz, Gerald J.; Merino, Donald N.; Tselios, Demetrios;Shroff, Vijay C.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>An overall review of nine fibre optic local area network systemsused today is made, in terms of topology (bus, star, ring), accessprotocol (CSMA/CD, token ring, etc.), and trade-offs (fibre type,bandwidth availability, access complexity, transport and accessdelay, reliability and costs, where applicable, etc.).andP;  The LANsare reviewed according to the IEEE 803.2 standards.andP;  In thecurrent fibre optic LANs the double-ring topology with timedivision multiple access and the circuit/packet switching mode isthe most widely used.andP;  An existing fibre optic LAN at the StevensInstitute of Technology, NJ, USA, is employed as a model todescribe costs involved in the realistic installation of a LAN.andO;The cost analysis review of the LAN model is based on the firstcost (material acquisition and installation), operational cost,and incremental expansion cost.andP;  (Reprinted by permission of thepublisher.)andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Local Area NetworksNetwork ArchitectureFiber OpticsCostProtocolComparisonCommunications TechnologyBandwidthConfiguration.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablechart.andO;Caption:   Basic fibre optic LAN types. (table)Two counter-rotating rings used by four stations. (chart)Failure at the same point on both fibre optic cables. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>